sp.p:
I am the Audience's very humble Servant;
but they cannot make a Man write a Prologue, whether
he can or no.

Sir, I desire no other Payment but of this small Bill;
your Worship's Cattle are saddled, and it is a charming Day for
travelling.

Do you think, Madam, this is the very same Don—;
what d'ye call him, whom your Father saw in Spain, and of
whom he has told us such pure pleasant Stories?

Beau Monde, Sir, is as much as to say, a Man of Figure;
when you say, he is a Man of the Beau Monde, you
mean just such another Person as I am.

His Frenzy! his Roguery; the Fellow's a Rogue;
he is no more mad than I am; and the Coachman and Landlord
both have very good Actions at Law against him.

A very hopeful Spark this. But he has a great Estate;
and I have no Notion of refusing an Estate, let the Man be
what he will.

'Fore George, a good pretty Wench; I'll have a Kiss;
I'll warrant she's twice as handsom as my Wife, that is to
be.

A Search of Adventures, Sir; no Place abounds more
with them. I was told there was a plenteous Stock of Monsters;
nor have I found one less than I expected.
